segments.text: Continuing the interview with Mr. Bruce Barber, who's in Vietnam.
We're discussing the effect of the anti-war feelings within the military.
Continue, please.
Well, as I said, I wasn't aware of any anti-war feelings either in the Air Force or I don't recall hearing any
in the other services.
That's just not the nature of the service.
That's like asking Aggies to root for Texas or something.
It wasn't there.
Maybe I didn't see it.
Maybe it was there at some levels, but I wasn't aware of it.
What were your thoughts or feelings when Saigon did fall in 1975?
Well, I thought it was sad.
All those people died, all that money, all that effort, and it was for nothing, really.
We tried to set up a democratic government in South Vietnam.
We failed.
The United States effort had to be pulled out primarily because of lack of support.
from the American people and thence the government, senators, congress.
We tried to Vietnamize the war by saying, okay, we're not going to send our people over here anymore to get killed, but we're going to give you all the stuff you need to fight this war.
And then we're going to gradually go back home and you can fight them.
Well, that didn't work.
The Vietnamese didn't have the will to win.
They didn't, you know, the South Vietnamese didn't.
The North Vietnamese did.
They cared a lot more and they were, you know, well-disciplined, motivated and in the end they just, you know, they took over the place.
Did you see the war perhaps as more of a civil war between South?
I mean, we pretty much created South Vietnam as an entity, but
Did you think it was more an internal struggle or was it more communism taking over?
I think it was communism taking over.
The North Vietnamese
communistic government, they wanted the South.
They got it.
They made a mess out of it and didn't do anything with it.
I didn't see it as a civil war.
Maybe part of it was that.

That's kind of a broad question, but do you think the Vietnam experiences, I mean obviously it's changed American foreign policy, but how would you see it as being detrimental to the policy in general or
I mean, do you think that now that Reagan's eight years as president has kind of brought us back to a pre-Vietnam sense of policy?
Well, I don't think so.
I don't think it's brought us back to that point at all.
Maybe we've gone back some distance.
But this country doesn't operate like it did 30 years ago.
If it did with a trouble spot like Lebanon and so forth,
And what happened over there, we'd have sent the troops in there and taken that place over and straightened that country out 30 years ago.
When the Iranians took over our embassy, we'd have gone in there and straightened that place out.
But we just don't do that anymore.
It's more a diplomatic approach.
We don't have the big military stick out there waving it around all the time.
and we're a lot less involved in other countries' business than we were.
There were some things that the CIA did in Vietnam and so forth in that time period that become public knowledge that has changed the way we do business a lot.
Would you draw a comparison between what's going on in Central America
with Vietnam.
And then another thing is kind of Reagan's approach to Vietnam was the fact that, you know, you mentioned Congress didn't let us win.
You were held back.
Do you think that that's, I mean, as far as like specifically in Central America?
Well, yeah, there's another example where, you know, that's a far more direct threat to the United States than South Vietnam ever was, or Korea.
And here we've got...
you know, a war and communist forces that I think pose a real threat to our security in the future.
I think those rascals will keep right on coming, and Mexico certainly is in bad shape to try and fend off any kind of internal struggle that they might get involved with.
I think that years ago, we'd have been right in the middle of that Nicaragua business.
But we're not going that way today.
The public won't support it.
The Congress won't support it.
We just got to try and work out a political answer.
And that may work and it may not.
Just one last question.
I mean as far as, what did you do when you were in Korea?
Were you a fighter pilot there?
I was right out of flight school, or right out of flying training of course, and I was mostly an air crew.
I was also, well we flew missions similar to those in Vietnam, but I was also an instructor, an instrument flying instructor, and I flew people in the
training planes a lot, teaching them instruments.
You always have to have a certain amount of instruments flying every year, wherever you are, and that kind of occupied a lot of my time, but I didn't do any staff work or anything at that time.
I was too young, really.
Could you, as far as the effort in Korea, I mean, comparable to Vietnam,
What would you tend to say about people that said, well, Korea, we just went in there and we did it right, and that's the way we should have done it in Vietnam, to this extent?
Well, Korea is different terrain, a different type of warfare, really.
We weren't fighting primarily guerrillas.
We were fighting regular forces.
and I think the South Koreans were more motivated than the South Vietnamese.
We did get back to the 38th parallel and established the kind of government we wanted, so it was a win in a sense.
I think we're actually losing control over there and we'll be back
on the opposite side of the fence pretty soon, but it was a different situation really.
Okay, well I guess that's all the questions I have unless you have any questions or anything you'd like to say?
I don't have anything else.
Scott, I think we covered about everything, all the questions.
I hope what I have said is some kind of meaningful and that you can make some kind of report after this.
Okay, well, thanks a lot.
Okay, you're welcome.
Hello, what are you doing?
Are you running out?
